posts.cooked: It seems like a great printer for FRC parts, although quite expensive. Another quick question, does anyone know if it does nylons and other engineering filaments well?

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
Most of the more advanced filaments (say, beyond PLA/PETG/TPU) call for an enclosure, either for warping or for gnarly fumes or for both.

This printer is neat and all, but I’d venture that 99.999% of FRC teams would be better suited with an armada of smaller printers.  $3k on the quad-nozzle OrangeStorm Giga buys six A1 Combos (with AMS Lite), or eight standard A1s, or a dozen A1 Minis.  All of which can sling different things at the same time.

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
I have both an A1 mini and a big printer of my own design that will do a 15” cube.  Honestly, -anything- I can run out on the mini goes there.  The print quality is better and its way faster!

However, the big guy is set up to do glass filled nylon and ABS, so its the go-to for things that need the highest strength/toughness.  And, of course, giant parts

The takeaway: all of the annoying things about printers get worse as they get bigger.  Levelling, speed, warping, bed adhesion, surface finish, taking up space, etc.  The little guys just work better for anything they can fit.  Of course, when you segment and glue parts the PITA factor gets out of control pretty quickly.  Plus, some of the non-stinky filaments are very hard to glue (PETG, I’m looking at you!).
